    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Elongate, slender scaleworm in which only the front half of the body bears scales, while the segments of the back half are naked and brown. The scales are characteristically each half chocolate-brown and half pale pink.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_2036",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Body length typically about 60 mm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_2037",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to Southern Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Southern Namibia to about False Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_2038",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Uncommon species usually seen singly, crawling under boulders or amongst other invertebrates, kelp holdfasts and the like.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_2039",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Carnivorous, feeding on small invertebrates.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_2040",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Little is know about reproduction in this group, but sexes are separate and it is assumed that eggs and sperm are released directly into the water column, where they develop into planktonic larvae.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_2041",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Scaleworms are easily recognised as a group, due to the flat dorsal scales that cover all or much of the body, but there are more than 50 species in the region and many of these are hard to distinguish at species level. Useful clues to species identification include number of pairs of scales, and whether these cover the whole, or only the front half of the body, as well as scale colour and ornamentation.</p><p>This genus is unusual in that the body is very elongate and only the front half of the segments bear scales. A second similar species <i>P. scolopendrina</i> occurs in the same region, but in that species the scales are rough and speckled with grey.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_2042",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2022). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fifth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 64).<br><br>Day, JH (1967). A Monograph on the Polychaeta of Southern Africa. British Museum (Natural History), London, Part. 1 Errantia (p. 55).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_2043",
